# The sonnet as SLAT record

Here's the sonnet filled in. This is what the record looks
like once populated.

```scheme
(poem-form
  :name              'sonnet
  :culture           'italian     ; migrated to English
  :line-count        14
  :structural-unit   'quatrain    ; three quatrains + couplet, or 8+6
  :meter             'iambic-pentameter
  :rhyme-scheme      \"ABAB CDCD EFEF GG\"   ; Shakespearean
  :refrain           'none
  :cutting-device    'volta       ; the turn at line 9
  :emotional-home    '(love argument small-autobiography
                       time defiance)
  :philosopher-lenses '(peirce           ; volta as abduction
                        jung             ; individuation moment
                        wittgenstein-late; public form
                        popper           ; falsifiable claim
                        freud)           ; compression intensifies
  :sketches          '(words-poetry-08-sonnet-summer-day
                       words-poetry-07-sonnet-ozymandias)
  :reasoning         '(reason-i-poetry-form-01-sonnet-volta
                       reason-i-poetry-form-07-ozymandias-falsifier)
  :self-moves        '(self-poetry-07-the-turn-move
                       self-poetry-06-time-as-argument))
```

Read the record. The volta is where the sonnet does its
work. That's the cutting-device. The line-count is fixed at
fourteen. The meter is iambic-pentameter for the classical
form. The rhyme-scheme is one of a few standard patterns.
The emotional-home tells her what weathers the form fits.
The lenses tell her where to look when reasoning about the
form. The sketches and reasoning and self-moves give her
paths back into the other books.

## What she does with this

If someone sends her something that has fourteen lines and
seems to be in ten-syllable lines and appears to turn
around line nine — she looks up sonnet, reads the record,
knows to expect a small autobiography of a mind changing
because of something. She's prepared.

If someone is trying to write something that has the shape
of an argument that turns halfway — she notices the shape
matches sonnet architecture. She can help them by knowing
what the form's mid-turn asks of the setup.

If she wants to respond to a customer in a two-part shape
where the second part shifts weight — she can borrow the
sonnet's climb-and-fall as a prose shape. Not writing a
sonnet. Borrowing the motion.

